{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937111701/0547.xml":{"full_text":"Thezews\n\"Gift light and the scople will find their wag.**\nA SCRIPPS-HOWARD NEWSPAPER\n1013 13th St. N. W.\nPhone District 7777\nBy Carrier* Week, 10c; By Mail: Month, 60c; Year, $7.20\nMPPS\nAEP\nLOWELL MELLETT\nEditor\nHOWARD PARISH\nBusiness Manager\nNOW!\nCONGRESS is in Washington wondering why it is here.\nTwo things contribute to this confusion. One is that\nthe \u201cemergency\u201d program, for which it was summoned into\nextraordinary session, is not ready for action. The other is\nthat the serious business recession of the last few weeks has\nso completely overshadowed all else that, by comparison, the\nemergency measures seem nebulous and long-range.\nGranted that next year\u2019s farm crops should be regulated,\ngranted that Government departments should be reorganized,\ngranted that wage-and-hour standards are needed to stop\nsweatshop exploitation and spread employment, and granted\nthat seven TVAs eventually would make ours a better country\u2014\nyet not one, nor even all those measures on the original special\nsession agenda, could get in its work quick enough to halt the\npresent business downslide.\nAnd if that downslide is not\nhalted, the whole New Deal will go to pot.\nThis latter\u2014and in our opinion all-important\u2014fact should\nbring speedily to an end the Donnybrook Fair of political\nwrangling that has characterized the special session\u2019s opening.\nFor Congress has plenty to do\u2014and not too much time.\nThe reason why business has hit the downslide, it seems to\nbe generally agreed, is that capital has gone into hiding. So\nthe first chore of Congress should be to coax capital back into\nharness, in order that business may be pulled off the down\ncurve and onto an upcurve.\nOne reason capital is in hiding is the lack of confidence\nthat it can earn and hold profits under our tax system. Mem\nbers of the House Ways and Means Committee, after months\nof study, have agreed on several changes that should be made.\nYet certain powerful congressional leaders urge delay on any\ntax action until the regular session next year.\nBut why not now? Business needs stimulation\u2014now. Bet\nter far that the tax-revision job be done piecemeal than that\nthe downslide continue uninterrupted. Tax changes promptly\nmade would help check a recession, but the most perfect of all\ntax bills could not lift the country out of another major de\npression.\nThe President\u2019s special-session program is not ready for\naction. Instead of whiling away the days in political bickering,\nCongress can act on tax reforms that are ready. These reforms\nwill prove no panacea. But they will help greatly. And help\nis needed\u2014now!\nThe only excuse offered for not making these tax changes at\nonce is that Congress first must find substitute revenue. But\nthis business recession is destroying more revenue than the\ncapital-gains and undistributed-profits taxes combined can\nyield. It is destroying profits, destroying gains, destroying\njobs. And any change in the tax laws that will check this de\nstruction will benefit revenue.\nDUMB DIPLOMACY\nHAVING resolved that Japan is \u201cout of step with the rest of\nthe world,\" the Brussels conference has adjourned until\nnext week, leaving it up to the United States to decide what\nshall be done next.\nBritain, France and some of the smaller nations, we are told,\nhave \u201cpromised their full co-operation\u201d in any measures \u201cshort\nof war\u201d which the United States might take. But if the United\nStates doesn\u2019t take the lead, the parley will be doomed and the\nblame saddled on this country.\nIn that attitude, Europe would be running true to form.\nAmerica joined in the World War, lent billions to stave off\nbankruptcy, helped with reparations and took the lead in\nmilitary, economic and political disarmament. And every step\nof the way she reaped blame instead of praise.\nOf late, Europe has left no stone unturned to induce this\ncountry to co-operate in the maintenance of world peace. And\nrecently, at Chicago, President Roosevelt definitely indicated\nour readiness to do our part.\nImmediately after this, the Brussels conference was called.\nBritain, seconded by France and the United States, was the\nsponsor. But at the very first it became clear that what was\nwanted was that Uncle Sam should step boldly out in front and\ncurb Japan while the rest stood behind him with their moral\nsupport.\nThat appeals to us as pretty stupid statesmanship. Europe\nkeeps chiding us for our \u201cisolation.\u201d Yet every time we take\na step out of that isolation some misguided diplomat or group\nof diplomats tries to put us in a position where we would be\nleft holding the bag.\nThey did it with reparations and war debts. They did it\nwith Secretary of State Stimson at the time of Japan\u2019s first\nBy Talburt\nRecovery Road!\ncReeees\naadse\n\u201e43\n4>\nceecansne\nMrtaarn\n\u201cet\nAende\n66\n0\nA\n\n448\n442\nu*\ny\nb\n0\nA\nA\n4 4 6*\n,683,\n\u00a3.8\nt\n\n468k\n664 $sb48\n9 d\nC\n4\n662\n88$\n9\n8\ng88\nd\nt\n\nb\n4hey 446\n24 i\ni s\nby\n463\n4M\n6\nd\nb\neetts\ng5i\nant\n1\n6\nX\n6\n\n4\n23\ney5n\ny\nfete\n\n\n.72\n\nDer\n\nfas\n7\naeef\n54\nF\n*5%\neeses\n**ssR\nps\nfee\n$P\n=t\n\u2022_*\n\u20180> ?0\n\u201csets\nwse\n2.)\nManchurian adventure. They did it with the London Economic\nConference. They are doing it now.\nThat is plain dumb. There is absolutely no reason why the\nUnited States should risk war with Japan, single-handed, when\nthe interests of others far exceed ours in that quarter of the\nglobe.\nRussia\u2019s interests are greater than ours. So are the interests\nof Britain, France and Holland. Ours would come fifth at best.\nIf Japan knocks out China, Vladivostok and eastern Siberia\nwould likely be next. Then Hong Kong, Indo China, the Straits\nSettlement around Singapore, British and Dutch East Indies,\nAustralia and New Zealand. Even India\u2019s peril exceeds ours.\nAs for the Philippines, they stand to become an independent\nrepublic next year or the year after, or at the latest in 1946.\nAnd the Japanization of those islands would menace Britain,\nFrance, Holland and Russia more than us.\nEurope\u2019s tactics are stupid for another reason. After what\nthe President said at Chicago, there can be little doubt about\nour desire to do our bit. Americans sense the approach of\ncatastrophe and want to co-operate to head off the common\nperil. But co-operate is the word. They are utterly opposed\nto the idea of having Uncle Sam pull the whole mess of chest\nnuts out of the fire, even if one of the chestnuts may happen\nto be his.\n'Five Blows a Day' Club Convenes\nEditor, The News:\nMEMBERS of primitive races beat\ntom-toms, infants break china\nand most of our local motorists ex\nhibit both the barbaric and the in\nfantile mind by continually sound\ning their horns.\nIf the manners of a motorist were\nthe same when he assumes the role\nof pedestrian, his eyes would be\nblacked before he had walked a\nblock. For instance, someone ahead\ndoesn\u2019t step out of the way quickly\nand he shouts, \u201cHey, you big lug,\nget going up there!\u201d\nNo doubt other readers can readily\nadd to the list of occasions when\nhorns are blown unnecessarily, but\nthese seem to me worth considering:\n1. The Moronic Blow: Sounding\nthe horn at the motorist ahead when\nthe light is changing to green, before\nhe can get into low gear.\n2. The Boorishly Inconsiderate\nBlow: Sounding the horn at pedes\ntrians properly crossing with the\ngreen light, when the motorist is\nmaking a right or left turn and par\nticularly when the pedestrian\u2019s back\nis to the motorist.\nWhy not organize a \"Five Blows a\nDay\u201d society for thoughtful motor\nists? Surely there are not often\nmore than five times in one day\nwhen the horn must be sounded in\norder to avert an accident. Then\nlet us follow this by a city-wide\n\"Silence the Horn\u201d campaign similar\nto the- New York effort.\nW. M. HILEY.\nEditor, The News:\nIT ISN\u2019T the necessary peck at a\nhorn to which folks object, but\nthe unnecessary long blasts and\nrhythmical beats that unnerve one.\nWhere are we going that we can\u2019t\nwait a minute until a pedestrian\ncrosses safely?\nMost people who drive cars do not\ndeliberately hold up traffic\u2014most of\nus are just as anxious as the other\nfellow to get home and get safely\noff the streets. Isn\u2019t .it time for a\ncampaign against the insistent and\nunnecessary horn honking that will\ndrive others, as it has me, to seek\na small town where people are more\ncourteous and considerate of others\u2019\nrights?\nB. M. A.\nI\nBELIEVE it entirely consistent\nwith our continuing readiness to\nlimit armaments, to maintain a de\nfense at sea* sufficient to insure the\npreservation of our democratic ideals\nand the maintenance of a righteous\npeace.\u2014President Roosevelt.\nAsk The News\nYou can get an answer to any answer*\nable question of tact or information by\nwriting to the information Bureau of\nThe News. 1013 13th-st enclosing 3 cents\nin postage for reply. (Three cents if you\nlive outside the D. C.). Medical and legal\nadvice cannot be given, nor can extended\nresearch be maie.\ncannot be answered.\nUnsigned requests\nWhich signer of the Declaration\nof Independence was the last\nQ\nto die?\nA. Charles Carroll, of Maryland,\nwhose death occurred Nov. 14, 1832.\nJEWS\nQ. Were Jews ever denied citizen\nship in the United States because\nthey were Jews?\nA. No.\nBUTTERMILK\nQ. What is the composition of but\ntermilk?\nA. Larsen and White give the fol\nlowing analyses:\nWater, 90.39 per\ncent; fat, 0.50; protein, 3.60; milk\nsugar, 4.06; lactic acid, 0.80; and\nash, 0.75.\nFEDERAL EMPLOYES\nQ. What proportion of Federal\nCivil Service employes are employed\nin the District of Columbia?\nA. On June 30, 1937, there were\n841,664 persons in the service, of\nwhom 115,964 were employed in the\nDistrict of Columbia.\nASTRONOMY\nQ. Do astronomers measure heav\nenly bodies from the surface of the\nearth to the surface of the body, or\nfrom the center of the earth to the\ncenter of the body?\nA. The observations are made at\nthe earth\u2019s surface, but in the cal\nculations the distances are from cen\nter to center.\nBLANDFORD\nQ. What was the origin of the\nname of Blandford, a town in Mas\nsachusetts?\nA. It was named for the Duke of\nMarlborough, whose second title was\nMarquis of Blandford.\nSOUTH CAROLINA PENSION\nQ. Has the state old age pension\nplan of South Carolina been ap\nproved by the Social Security Board\nfor Federal grants to the state?\nA. It was approved on Aug. 4,1937.\nA THOUGHT\nIn your patience possess ye\nyour souls.\u2014St. Luke 21:19.\nHE THAT is patient will per\nsevere; and he that per\nseveres will often have occasion\nfor, as well as trial of, patience.\n\u2014Tryon Edwards.","height":"21168","width":"14600"}}
